Project Link - https://tableau-project.utksahu30.workers.dev/


Project Architecture
The project follows a standard static web structure, utilizing Semantic HTML5 for structure and Modern CSS3 (including variables and Flex/Grid) for a cohesive, dark-themed aesthetic.
1. Navigation & Global Layout
Every page shares a consistent site-header containing:
Brand Identity: "Housing Market Analysis" link.
Navigation Menu: Links to Home, Dashboard, Story, and About.
Active States: The active class is dynamically applied to the current page link to provide visual feedback to the user.
2. Technology Stack
Frontend: HTML5, CSS3 (Custom properties/Variables).
Data Visualization: Tableau Public (via JavaScript API embedding).
Styling: Responsive Design with a focus on dark mode UI, using gradients and backdrop-filter for a modern "glassmorphism" feel.
Animations: CSS @keyframes (fade-up) are used to create a staggered entry effect as the user scrolls or loads the page.

Page Breakdown
Home (index.html)
The entry point of the application. It focuses on high-level summaries.
Hero Section: Features a bold mission statement with a call-to-action (CTA) button leading to the dashboard.
Project Overview: A placeholder section for describing the dataset and methodology.
Key Insights Grid: A 3-column layout (on desktop) that highlights:
Price Drivers: Factors influencing home value.
Neighborhood Trends: Geographic analysis.
Market Signals: Outliers and seasonal trends.
Dashboard (dashboard.html)
This is the primary analytical tool of the site.
Embedding: Uses an <object> tag to embed a Tableau workbook (ProjectFinalWorkbook/Dashboard1).
Responsive Logic: Includes a custom <script> that calculates the container width and adjusts the height of the Tableau iframe dynamically to ensure the visualization remains legible on mobile, tablet, and desktop.
Story (story.html)
Similar to the dashboard page, but specifically displays a Tableau Story (ProjectFinalWorkbook/Story2).
Purpose: Whereas the dashboard is for exploration, the "Story" page is designed for a guided narrative, walking users through specific findings in a sequential format.
About (about.html)
Provides context on the "why" and "how" of the project.
The Vision: Explains the goal of merging data science with storytelling.
Tech Stack Details: Mentions the use of Python for data preparation and Tableau for visualization.
Project Objectives: Clearly lists identifying price drivers and supporting interactive exploration as core goals.

Design & Styling (style.css)
The visual identity is defined by a sophisticated dark theme:
Color Palette:
Background (--bg): Dark Charcoal (#111111).
Accent (--accent): Bold Red (#E6232E), used for buttons and active states.
Surface (--surface): Lighter grey (#1A1A1A) to create depth.
Responsiveness:
Desktop: Uses grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr) for cards.
Tablets/Mobile: Media queries collapse grids into single columns and adjust navigation links to wrap, ensuring usability on small screens.
Special Effects:
Gradients: Backgrounds use subtle radial gradients to prevent the dark theme from looking "flat."
Animations: The .reveal class triggers a subtle upward slide and fade-in when pages load.

How it Works: The Tableau Integration
The most complex part of the code is the script located at the bottom of dashboard.html and story.html.
Injection: It creates a new <script> element to fetch the official Tableau API (viz_v1.js).
Sizing Engine: The adjustDashboardSize() function detects the browser width:
> 900px: Sets height to 82% of width.
560px - 900px: Sets height to 112% of width.
< 560px (Mobile): Forces a tall 1800px height to accommodate stacked mobile charts.
Event Listeners: The script listens for the window.resize event to recalculate these dimensions instantly if a user rotates their phone or resizes their browser.

